# SCIPE AI in Civil Engineering

## Graduate Student Fellowship & Undergraduate Research Scholarship

The SCIPE AI in Civil Engineering fellowship and scholarship programs provide an opportunity to develop advanced Artificial Intelligence and Cyber Infrastructure for applications in Civil Engineering while collaborating with experts at UT Austin and TACC. The fellowship is a year-long program for graduate students; the scholarship is a summer-long program for undergraduate students.

## Graduate Student Fellowship

Program Dates: **June 1, 2025 – May 31, 2026**  

Application Deadline: **February 7, 2025 at 11:59 pm ET**

[Application Instructions](/education/undergraduates-graduates/scipe/fellowship-application-instructions)

#### Fellows will receive:

* $37,000 stipend in two installments of $18,500
* Up to $12,000 in tuition allowance throughout the year
* Travel support to present research results at a SCIPE AI in Civil Engineering community event and/or professional conference
* Paid visits to UT Austin and TACC in Austin, TX

We are committed to fostering an inclusive and diverse workplace. We strongly encourage applicants from all backgrounds, genders, races, ethnicities, sexual orientations, and disability statuses to apply.

For more information and to apply, please see **[Fellowship Application Instructions](/education/undergraduates-graduates/scipe/fellowship-application-instructions)** and  **[SCIPE FAQ](/education/undergraduates-graduates/scipe/faq)** or contact staff at: [scipe@tacc.utexas.edu](mailto:scipe@tacc.utexas.edu).

### Eligibility

**Applications will only be accepted from students who are studying in the United States or its territories at a US institution. Applicants must also:**

* Be enrolled as a PhD graduate student at the time of application
* Have completed at least one academic year (2 full semesters) of their graduate program as of March 2025
* Have at least one full academic year remaining in their program as of June 2025
* Be able to spend at least one week of the summer semester in residence at TACC in the year of award

**Applications will be evaluated based on:**

* Related experience and service
* Research plan and its use of advanced computing resources
* Letters of reference
* Projects that support multidisciplinary research

## Undergraduate Research Scholarship

Program Dates: **June 1, 2025 – June 30, 2025**  

Application Deadline: **February 7, 2025 at 11:59 pm ET**

[Application Instructions](/education/undergraduates-graduates/scipe/scholarship-application-instructions)

#### Scholarship awardees will receive:

* Stipend of $7,000, includes maintenance allowance for time at UT Austin/TACC.
* Paid travel to UT Austin and TACC in Austin, TX

We are committed to fostering an inclusive and diverse workplace. We strongly encourage applicants from all backgrounds, genders, races, ethnicities, sexual orientations, and disability statuses to apply.

For more information and to apply, please see [**Scholarship Application Instruction**s](/education/undergraduates-graduates/scipe/scholarship-application-instructions) and  **[SCIPE FAQ](/education/undergraduates-graduates/scipe/faq)** or contact staff at: [scipe@tacc.utexas.edu](mailto:scipe@tacc.utexas.edu).

### Eligibility

**Applications will only be accepted from students who are studying in the United States or its territories at a US institution. Applicants must also:**

* Be enrolled as an undergraduate student at the time of application
* Have completed at least one academic year (2 full semesters) of their undergraduate program as of March 2025
* Have at least one full academic year remaining in their program as of June 2025
* Be able to spend at least one month of the summer semester in residence at UT Austin/TACC in the year of award

**Applications will be evaluated based on:**

* Related experience and service
* Research plan and its use of advanced computing resources
* Letters of reference
* Projects that support multidisciplinary research

*The SCIPE Graduate Student Fellowship and Undergraduate Research Scholarship are supported by the [Chishiki-AI](https://www.chishiki-ai.org/) program, a pioneering initiative funded by the National Science Foundation and led by a team of experts at the University of Texas at Austin in collaboration with Cornell University.*